DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(84)80047-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426684800473
AB  - Since Eurocurrency deposits normally bear an interest rate that exceeds domestic bank deposit rates, many have assumed that Eurodeposits are necessarily riskier then domestic deposits. The authors dispute this. They dissect the legal and practical facets of Eurocurrency deposit risk. concluding that it is possible to build a matrix of sovereign risks governing Eurocurrency deposits and to assemble a combination that minimizes risk for any particular depositor. International banks, therefore, do have some influence over the degree of sovereign risk faced by the depositor.
